'''Hackpad''' is a [[web-based]] [[collaborative real-time text editor]] forked from [[Etherpad]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/dropbox/hackpad/blob/master/LICENSE|title=dropbox/hackpad|website=GitHub|language=en|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref>.
In April 2014, Hackpad was acquired by [[Dropbox (service)|Dropbox]].<ref name="wsj">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2014/04/17/dropbox-acquires-startups-loom-hackpad-in-push-to-expand-services/|title=Dropbox Acquires Startups Loom, Hackpad in Push to Expand Services|author=Mike Billings|work=WSJ|accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hackpad.com/Hackpad-is-teaming-up-with-Dropbox-m1Fne5A6Lzn|title=Hackpad is teaming up with Dropbox!|work=hackpad.com|accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref> In April 2015, it was announced that Hackpad would be released as open source<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/bryanlanders/status/586235797571002368/photo/1|title=Bryan Landers on Twitter}}</ref> and source code was published on Github in August 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/dropbox/hackpad|title=Dropbox's Hackpad GitHub repository}}</ref> under the [[Apache license]] 2.0.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/dropbox/hackpad/blob/master/COPYING|title=Hackpad COPYING file}}</ref> On April 25, 2017, Hackpad announced that it is to shut down on July 19, 2017, permanently migrating to [[Dropbox Paper]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dropbox.com/help/9156|title=Hackpad is migrating to Dropbox Paper}}</ref>
