{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}{{Infobox person | name =Pauline Gower | image =Pauline_Gower.jpg | image_size = | caption =Pauline Gower at a Women's Engineering Society awards dinner in the 1940s | birth_name =Pauline Mary de Peauly Gower | birth_date = 22 July 1910 | birth_place = [[Tonbridge]], [[Kent]], England | death_date = {{dda|1947|3|2|1910|7|22|df=y}}<ref name="times">{{cite news |title= Mrs. W. C. Fahie|work=[[The Times]] |publisher=The Times Digital Archive |page=7 |date=4 March 1947 }}</ref> | death_place = [[Royal Tunbridge Wells]], Kent, England | death_cause = | residence = | nationality = British | other_names = | ethnicity = | education = | occupation = [[Aviator|Pilot]] | father =[[Robert Vaughan Gower|Sir Robert Gower]] | spouse ={{marriage|William Cusack Fahie|1945}} | awards = | networth = }} '''Pauline Mary de Peauly Gower Fahie''' (22 July 1910 &ndash; 2 March 1947) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] pilot and writer who established the women's branch of the [[Air Transport Auxiliary]] during the [[Second World War]].
==Early life and education==
Daughter of [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[Robert Vaughan Gower|Sir Robert Gower]], and educated at [[Beechwood Sacred Heart School]], she first flew with [[Alan Cobham]] and was fascinated by flying. Gower met [[Dorothy Spicer]] at the London Aeroplane Club at [[Stag Lane Aerodrome]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-67672|title=Spicer [married name Pearse], Dorothy Norman (1908–1946), aviator and aeronautical engineer|last=Fahie|first=Michael|date=2004-09-23|publisher=Oxford University Press|series=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/67672}}</ref> and they became friends. In August 1931 they established a joy-riding and air taxi service in Kent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theiet.org/resources/library/archives/research/wes/WES_Vol_3a.html|title="Thirteenth Annual Report". The Woman Engineer. The Institution of Engineering and Technology. 3 (12): 189.|last=|first=|date=October 1932|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> Gower was licensed to carry passengers for 'hire or reward', and Spicer was qualified as a ground engineer and held an 'A' (private) pilot's licence. They hired a plane and later bought a [[De Havilland Gypsy Moth|Gypsy Moth]] for the business, but struggled to make a living so decided to join the [[Crimson Fleet]] air circus and later the British Hospitals' air pageant.
In 1932, to support British Hospitals, they toured the country with an Air Circus, giving air pageants in 200 towns.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Women's Engineer (1929 - 1934) |journal=theiet.org|date=|volume=3|url=http://www.theiet.org/resources/library/archives/research/wes/WES_Vol_3a.html|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref> They joined the Aeronautical Section of the [[Women's Engineering Society]] in 1932.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theiet.org/resources/library/archives/research/wes/WES_Vol_3a.html|title="News of Members". The Woman Engineer. The Institution of Engineering and Technology. 3 (15): 247|last=|first=|date=June 1933|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> Gower also wrote for ''[[Girl's Own Paper]]'' and ''[[Chatterbox (paper)|Chatterbox]]'' and published a collection of poetry, ''Piffling Poems for Pilots'', in 1934. As a writer she was acquainted with [[W. E. Johns]] whose character [[Worrals]] was based on herself as well as [[Amy Johnson]].{{cn|date=February 2016}}
==Engineering work== [[File:Pauline Gower, Commandant of the Air Transport Auxiliary Women's Section, waving from the cockpit of a de Havilland Tiger Moth at Hatfield, Hertfordshire, prior to a delivery flight, 10 January 1940. C380.jpg|left|thumb|Gower in the cockpit of a de Havilland Tiger Moth]] In 1935 she was appointed as a council member for the [[Women's Engineering Society]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Women Engineer|journal=theiet.org|year=1935|volume=4|pages=62-63|url=http://www.theiet.org/resources/library/archives/research/wes/WES_Vol_4a.html|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref> She chaired a meeting on "The History of British Airships", where Mr. M. Langley championed the airboat and Hon. A. F. de Moleyns the airship.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Women's Engineer|journal=theiet.org|date=1935|volume=4|pages=94-95|url=http://www.theiet.org/resources/library/archives/research/wes/WES_Vol_4a.html|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref> In 1936, Gower was the first woman to be awarded the [[Air Ministry]]'s Second Class Navigator's Licence.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Women's Engineer|journal=theiet.org|date=1935|volume=4|pages=104-1055|url=http://www.theiet.org/resources/library/archives/research/wes/WES_Vol_4a.html|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref> Later that year, Gower and her colleague [[Dorothy Spicer]] ('daring aeronauts') presented a technical paper at the Women's Engineering Society Annual General Meeting on the treatment of metals for aircraft engineers. <ref>{{cite journal|title=The Women's Engineer|journal=theiet.org|date=1935|volume=4|pages=204-205|url=http://www.theiet.org/resources/library/archives/research/wes/WES_Vol_4a.html|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref> In 1938, she was appointed a civil defence commissioner in [[London]] with the [[Civil Air Guard]]. That year her work on women in aviation&mdash;''Women with Wings''&mdash;was published.<ref>Merry, Lois K. [https://books.google.com/books?id=oBIi6ezWZ0IC&pg=PA66&dq=gremlin+1920s&hl=en&ei=EB4STfzZHpCyhAehs9y2Dg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=gremlin%201920s&f=false ''Women Military Pilots of World War II: A History with Biographies of American, British, Russian and German Aviators.''] Jefferson, North Carolina: McFarland & Company Inc., 2010. {{ISBN|978-0-7864-4441-0}}</ref> On the outbreak of the [[Second World War]], Gower made use of her high-level connections to propose the establishment of a women's section in the new [[Air Transport Auxiliary]] &mdash;the ATA would be responsible for ferrying military aircraft from factory or repair facility to storage unit or operational unit&mdash;to the authorities. [[file:Five ATA flyers Lettice Curtis Jenny Broad Audrey Sale Barker Gabrielle Patterson and Pauline Gower.jpg|thumb|Five ATA flyers [[Lettice Curtis]], [[Jenny Broad]], [[Audrey Sale Barker]], [[Gabrielle Patterson]] and Gower]] Gower was appointed as the head of the women's branch, and commenced the selection and testing of women pilots, the first eight being appointed by the ATA on 1 January 1940. Early members included ice-hockey international [[Mona Friedlander]], [[Margaret Fairweather]] ([[Walter Runciman, 1st Viscount Runciman of Doxford|Lord Runciman]]'s daughter) and former ballet dancer [[Rona Rees]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.airtransportaux.com/firsteight.html|title=ATA First Eight|website=www.airtransportaux.com|access-date=2016-10-28}}</ref> Later members included [[Amy Johnson]] and former Olympic skier [[Lois Butler]]. Gower received the [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] for her services in 1942<ref name="times"/> and received a [[Harmon Trophy]] award posthumously in 1950.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://0-find.galegroup.com.catalogue.wellcomelibrary.org/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=wellcome&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=&docId=CS119358564&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|title=Mrs. W. C. Fahie|last=|first=|date=4 March 1947|work=The Times (London, England)|access-date=28 October 2016|via=Gale}}</ref> {{-}}
==Personal life== Gower married Wing Commander Bill Fahie in 1945. She died in 1947 giving birth to twin sons, who survived.<ref name="times"/><ref>[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1947/1947%20-%200329.html Notice of Pauline Fahie's death], flightglobal.com, 13 March 1947.</ref>
